Media notes: Predating on plains garter snake.
Observation Details: I've seen this red-tailed hawk at the lake many times, but today as I was crossing the prairie area to the southwest, she swooped down into the field. It looked as if she was picking at something on the ground, and it turned out to be a garter snake! She pecked at it a few times, and followed the snake for about 5 yards stomping on it with her talons as it tried to make an escape, before finally getting a hold of it in her beak. Super cool to see this common predator in action!

Continuing; photos. This bird is very interesting. It's beginning to molt and has lost the two innermost primaries, so hopefully if it hangs around another few weeks we'll see what those new adult flight feathers look like. This bird could be an intergrade with calurus, but it has very broad barring on the secondaries, and the tail, and the tip of the tail has at least a partial 'spike' at the tips shown by most juv dark harlani. The bases of the tail feathers and some primaries have vague mottling already. It would be great if this bird returned as an adult next fall, but I fear this field will be nothing but strawberries by the time it gets back.

Media notes: All juv photos are the same individual
Observation Details: Photos of 2

Potentially the most stunning encounter I've had in my life. Absolutely gorgeous and fearless Red-Tailed Hawk. I saw it sitting in the trees and pulled over to try and take a few pictures when it flew down to eye level and perched in a leafless shrub. There it sat looking around seemingly perch hunting. I was very close to it already so I walked a bit closer. The hawk watched me intently and with curiosity as I approached but remained very calm the whole time. Eventually, I got within FIVE FEET of the hawk. If I had leaned forward I would have been able to pet its head. It was surreal seeing a completely wild hawk so close. As I got within that limit, the hawk started flinching so I stopped approaching and backed up a tiny bit so I didn't stress him. Then after staring at me for a while he went back to his business, looking around and also preening. I sat there for nearly a half hour with a wild Red-Tailed Hawk just feet ahead of me at nearly eye level. It was absolutely gorgeous. Finally, after nearly a half hour of sitting beside him, the hawk leaped off the branch and flew to a lamp post. I left him after that. Wow that was an insane encounter!!!  He (or she) was a young bird currently molting into adult plumage. Part of its fearlessness may have been due to its young age.

Locality: Lake St. Clair Metropark (Metro Beach Metropark)

Observation Details: Presumed "Northern" RTHA (abieticola); stunning adult; prominent dark belly band; dark head and throat, the latter almost completely so, with markings extending into belly band; bold patagial marks; dark upperparts; deep red uppertail with partial barring; photos.   Dorsal notes were taken strictly off photos as I only really saw the underside well before I started shooting and only saw the upperside briefly through camera.  Today's bird was a brief encounter as it made a quick but stunning and close pass in great light then circled once before being carried east by strong winds. I've resisted seperating these on eBird till now but as long as reports are well described (or better yet photographed) then ebirding these should only help our understanding.

Observation Details: All adults. Two on usual nest above entrance road, briefly tangling with a second pair that flew by. Fifth bird was soaring in the distance as we watched the vultures. As has been noted in the past, these birds are quite heavily marked for typical borealis RTHA and are quite reminiscent of abieticola. Not sure if a hybrid had ever been recorded between those two ssp, but this is what I imagine it would look like (because there’s no way this is 100% pure borealis based on current plumage understanding).

Very broad, wavy tail bands with typical juvenile harlani tail tip. It's unusual for a juvenile dark harlani in having solidly black outer primary tips, but in this case tail pattern trumps all other field marks. Flight feather banded in broad, like harlani too. Jerry Liguori mentions only knowing of a few other examples like this.

Locality: Apple Rd south of Forman Rd

Observation Details: Potentially the most stunning encounter I've had in my life. Absolutely gorgeous and fearless Red-Tailed Hawk. I saw it sitting in the trees and pulled over to try and take a few pictures when it flew down to eye level and perched in a leafless shrub. There it sat looking around seemingly perch hunting. I was very close to it already so I walked a bit closer. The hawk watched me intently and with curiosity as I approached but remained very calm the whole time. Eventually, I got within FIVE FEET of the hawk. If I had leaned forward I would have been able to pet its head. It was surreal seeing a completely wild hawk so close. As I got within that limit, the hawk started flinching so I stopped approaching and backed up a tiny bit so I didn't stress him. Then after staring at me for a while he went back to his business, looking around and also preening. I sat there for nearly a half hour with a wild Red-Tailed Hawk just feet ahead of me at nearly eye level. It was absolutely gorgeous. Finally, after nearly a half hour of sitting beside him, the hawk leaped off the branch and flew to a lamp post. I left him after that. Wow that was an insane encounter!!!  He (or she) was a young bird currently molting into adult plumage. Part of its fearlessness may have been due to its young age.

Discovered Robin nest above rear door of nature center. Hoping around upper deck and metal bars above second floor door. You could see the gears turning as it tried to figure out how to get to the nest. Several Robins and Blue jays were dive bombing, and became so intense at one point the Red-tail left. Two more fly-bys, and the Red-tail landed in a tall tree. I assumed the Red-tail had given up, but swooped down from  the tree, talons fully extended, and rammed strait into the nest like a wrecking ball. Scooped out 1 baby bird, and quickly flew off and landed on a nearby branch to dine. Many more birds joined the assault, until the Red-tail flew off into the deeper woods. Checked the nest and the other babies (2) were just fine, but I fear it won't be long before the Red-tail comes back. Incredible experience!

One of my cooler raptor experiences. At least two, and possibly three immature birds were incredibly active towards the point - fighting and scraping with each other, and flying incredibly low right overhead multiple times. Once, one of them flew less than 10 feet over my head - they seemed to show absolutely no fear of humans.  One immature bird flew out over the water, towards UMass, which seemed pretty odd.  The second immature bird, which stayed and hunted around the point, hand a metal band, but no plastic band. Sure enough, as I turned the corner, scanning woodlot edges, I spotted a resident-type overlooking the meadow along the creek. This bird at first glance was small, with a flash of colour and buff below. It came in and then retreated to perch nearby, and in the time before I captured it a second larger, whiter bird had also appeared to perch close and watch. Presumably a resident pair.  Captured bird banded 2077-15567; 1M, after third cycle, but iris just pale enough that at first I thought I might expect it to be a younger bird.   Data collected as part of the Red-tailed Hawk Project. To learn more, please visit: https://redtailedhawkproject.org/

Potentially the most stunning encounter I've had in my life. Absolutely gorgeous and fearless Red-Tailed Hawk. I saw it sitting in the trees and pulled over to try and take a few pictures when it flew down to eye level and perched in a leafless shrub. There it sat looking around seemingly perch hunting. I was very close to it already so I walked a bit closer. The hawk watched me intently and with curiosity as I approached but remained very calm the whole time. Eventually, I got within FIVE FEET of the hawk. If I had leaned forward I would have been able to pet its head. It was surreal seeing a completely wild hawk so close. As I got within that limit, the hawk started flinching so I stopped approaching and backed up a tiny bit so I didn't stress him. Then after staring at me for a while he went back to his business, looking around and also preening. I sat there for nearly a half hour with a wild Red-Tailed Hawk just feet ahead of me at nearly eye level. It was absolutely gorgeous. Finally, after nearly a half hour of sitting beside him, the hawk leaped off the branch and flew to a lamp post. I left him after that. Wow that was an insane encounter!!!  He (or she) was a young bird currently molting into adult plumage. Part of its fearlessness may have been due to its young age.

Reporting on behalf of James Hawley. Adults. One bird is a young adult by presence of pale irides. James and I discussed his observations and both admired his excellent photos of one of the birds. Each bird is characteristic in plumage: deep brown/auburn head with wisps of golden throughout, streaks to upper breast leading to extensive, blackish belly band composed of messy globular-shaped markings, dark brown almost blackish mantle and upperparts with a reduction of pale spotting. The individuals he has photographed have had a penchant for perching on the very tips of coniferous trees. Perch orientation typically shows one foot lifted well above the other for balance. It is wonderful to admire these northern, boreal-breeding RTs during fall and winter. Deep-forest RTs from remote haunts....the east's harlani!

Observation Details: I first saw the adult bird in the photos on a pole along the north side Hospital Road, very close to the railroad tracks.  It noticed me but seemed untroubled by my presence.  After some preening, the bird made as if it was ready to take off, and an instant later flew into brush about fifty feet from the pole, where it made a bit of a racket in the leaves.  The bird emerged with a chipmunk, carrying it (along with a fallen leaf or two) in a single claw, flew further into the woods, perched where it was still visible from the road, and began to eat.

Potentially the most stunning encounter I've had in my life. Absolutely gorgeous and fearless Red-Tailed Hawk. I saw it sitting in the trees and pulled over to try and take a few pictures when it flew down to eye level and perched in a leafless shrub. There it sat looking around seemingly perch hunting. I was very close to it already so I walked a bit closer. The hawk watched me intently and with curiosity as I approached but remained very calm the whole time. Eventually, I got within FIVE FEET of the hawk. If I had leaned forward I would have been able to pet its head. It was surreal seeing a completely wild hawk so close. As I got within that limit, the hawk started flinching so I stopped approaching and backed up a tiny bit so I didn't stress him. Then after staring at me for a while he went back to his business, looking around and also preening. I sat there for nearly a half hour with a wild Red-Tailed Hawk just feet ahead of me at nearly eye level. It was absolutely gorgeous. Finally, after nearly a half hour of sitting beside him, the hawk leaped off the branch and flew to a lamp post. I left him after that. Wow that was an insane encounter!!!  He (or she) was a young bird currently molting into adult plumage. Part of its fearlessness may have been due to its young age.

Continuing; photos. This bird is very interesting. It's beginning to molt and has lost the two innermost primaries, so hopefully if it hangs around another few weeks we'll see what those new adult flight feathers look like. This bird could be an intergrade with calurus, but it has very broad barring on the secondaries, and the tail, and the tip of the tail has at least a partial 'spike' at the tips shown by most juv dark harlani. The bases of the tail feathers and some primaries have vague mottling already. It would be great if this bird returned as an adult next fall, but I fear this field will be nothing but strawberries by the time it gets back.

Potentially the most stunning encounter I've had in my life. Absolutely gorgeous and fearless Red-Tailed Hawk. I saw it sitting in the trees and pulled over to try and take a few pictures when it flew down to eye level and perched in a leafless shrub. There it sat looking around seemingly perch hunting. I was very close to it already so I walked a bit closer. The hawk watched me intently and with curiosity as I approached but remained very calm the whole time. Eventually, I got within FIVE FEET of the hawk. If I had leaned forward I would have been able to pet its head. It was surreal seeing a completely wild hawk so close. As I got within that limit, the hawk started flinching so I stopped approaching and backed up a tiny bit so I didn't stress him. Then after staring at me for a while he went back to his business, looking around and also preening. I sat there for nearly a half hour with a wild Red-Tailed Hawk just feet ahead of me at nearly eye level. It was absolutely gorgeous. Finally, after nearly a half hour of sitting beside him, the hawk leaped off the branch and flew to a lamp post. I left him after that. Wow that was an insane encounter!!!  He (or she) was a young bird currently molting into adult plumage. Part of its fearlessness may have been due to its young age.

Observation Details: I first saw the adult bird in the photos on a pole along the north side Hospital Road, very close to the railroad tracks.  It noticed me but seemed untroubled by my presence.  After some preening, the bird made as if it was ready to take off, and an instant later flew into brush about fifty feet from the pole, where it made a bit of a racket in the leaves.  The bird emerged with a chipmunk, carrying it (along with a fallen leaf or two) in a single claw, flew further into the woods, perched where it was still visible from the road, and began to eat.

Discovered Robin nest above rear door of nature center. Hoping around upper deck and metal bars above second floor door. You could see the gears turning as it tried to figure out how to get to the nest. Several Robins and Blue jays were dive bombing, and became so intense at one point the Red-tail left. Two more fly-bys, and the Red-tail landed in a tall tree. I assumed the Red-tail had given up, but swooped down from  the tree, talons fully extended, and rammed strait into the nest like a wrecking ball. Scooped out 1 baby bird, and quickly flew off and landed on a nearby branch to dine. Many more birds joined the assault, until the Red-tail flew off into the deeper woods. Checked the nest and the other babies (2) were just fine, but I fear it won't be long before the Red-tail comes back. Incredible experience!

Observation Details: Light adult. Mostly gray tail mottled with fine black streaks, and definitely gray rather than the normal paleness of a regular RT tail. Remiges extremely varied in barring but all on a gray base, with some feathers having a lot of fine black marks, and others having wider barring. Heavy blotched belly band and heavy dark patagials.Heavily marked underwing coverts. Snowier white underside giving a much colder-looking apperance than the usual warm browns/oranges of most non-Harlan's.   Borealis aren't so gray/cold throughout, especially in the tail and remiges. Both borealis and abeticola have much more consistent barring in the underwings, while this bird varies almost by the feather.   I'm ashamed to say that I only noticed this upon reviewing photos a week later. Apologies to anyone who would have potentially tried for it that day. To my knowledge this is the first light Harlan's photographed in Wisconsin.

Locality: High Rock Park--Paulo's Peak (formerly Moses Mtn.)
Observation Details: Very (very very) few records for these dark, heavily marked northern redtails on ebird for the coastal NYC/Long Island region, but presumably this is due to the lack of birders hawkwatching and identifying migrant redtails to subspecies, and photographing them. This bird appeared directly over the ridge and caught my eye as a potential abieticola right away, and I excitedly asked AT to photograph it. The photo confirms a dark redtail, with a dark chin, coarse, dark reddish streaking on what would be unmarked white underparts on a standard eastern bird, and much darker, more chocolate-color tones in the belly band, patagials, upperparts, etc. The belly band is also splattery, and widens at the edges where they meet the axillaries. Dusky border on wings sort of blown out by the sun in the photo. Shared photo with Red-tailed Hawks Of the United States on facebook, and folks more knowledgeable than I seem to agree with my guess.

Media notes: Staring at the crows after one of many passes
Observation Details: INTENSE moment observed! I saw this adult along Carisbrook being hounded by AMCR and staring intently at a patch of thick trees and bush. Not wanting to spoil what may be about to happen, I stopped in my tracks and just watched. The RTHA then plummeted down into the thick branches, just as I have seen in falconry videos, but never IRL - high speed but with what I'll call 'umbrella'-like wings (held in a high dihedral with quick descent and sharp turns) - and it captured an Eastern Grey Squirrel - only the AMCR were not having it. They mobbed the RTHA immediately and he or she dropped the catch, with the squirrel hitting the gravel road with a horrifying 'THUD'. After a few tense milliseconds of wondering whether it was dead, the squirrel came to and scurried off into the thick bush again. Meanwhile, the RTHA wanted another go but the AMCR would not leave it alone. I took a couple rounds of photos as I passed by it and then left them all alone to continue playing out the circle of life, hopefully with the squirrel eventually ending up being a meal for this hard-working raptor. The second individual was a high-flyover at the other end with a different looking belly band.

The rabbit did eventually make a sprint for it and the hawk pursued so I don't know the ending to this story! (Photo's)

Returning 2nd-year individual wintering at this location from October 2017 to March 2018, confirmed by pattern of retained juvenile secondaries and outer primaries, behavior. As suspected, this bird appears to be an intergrade between Harlan's and probably calurus. Harlan's characters here are mostly visible in the flight feathers, which are heavily banded with a thick, irregular pattern, and the bases of the primaries are mottled gray. The tail is mostly red, with some banding restricted to the base--the latter character seen in many Red-tailed Hawk subspecies breeding in the far north, but also rarely occurs in calurus. As I suspected in my notes on this individual from 23 March 2018, much of the habitat here is now gone, converted to strawberry fields. We'll see if this bird can make a living here this winter. Here's a link to what this bird looked like just before it departed last spring: https://ebird.org/view/checklist/S43896591.

Locality: Texas A&M Univ.--Ecology & Natural Resource area

Observation Details: Potentially the most stunning encounter I've had in my life. Absolutely gorgeous and fearless Red-Tailed Hawk. I saw it sitting in the trees and pulled over to try and take a few pictures when it flew down to eye level and perched in a leafless shrub. There it sat looking around seemingly perch hunting. I was very close to it already so I walked a bit closer. The hawk watched me intently and with curiosity as I approached but remained very calm the whole time. Eventually, I got within FIVE FEET of the hawk. If I had leaned forward I would have been able to pet its head. It was surreal seeing a completely wild hawk so close. As I got within that limit, the hawk started flinching so I stopped approaching and backed up a tiny bit so I didn't stress him. Then after staring at me for a while he went back to his business, looking around and also preening. I sat there for nearly a half hour with a wild Red-Tailed Hawk just feet ahead of me at nearly eye level. It was absolutely gorgeous. Finally, after nearly a half hour of sitting beside him, the hawk leaped off the branch and flew to a lamp post. I left him after that. Wow that was an insane encounter!!!  He (or she) was a young bird currently molting into adult plumage. Part of its fearlessness may have been due to its young age.

It was only 10 ft away, oblivious of my presence! I also shot 1 minute of video, which showed it performing an odd "fluffing and hunching" behavior (I know it sounds weird!). I suspect it is a behavior for bathing, but as can be seen the pool was way to small for that.

Continuing; photos. This bird is very interesting. It's beginning to molt and has lost the two innermost primaries, so hopefully if it hangs around another few weeks we'll see what those new adult flight feathers look like. This bird could be an intergrade with calurus, but it has very broad barring on the secondaries, and the tail, and the tip of the tail has at least a partial 'spike' at the tips shown by most juv dark harlani. The bases of the tail feathers and some primaries have vague mottling already. It would be great if this bird returned as an adult next fall, but I fear this field will be nothing but strawberries by the time it gets back.

Media notes: Light phase "Harlan's" Red-tailed Hawk, El Dorado Hills, El Dorado County, California
Observation Details: Continuing light phase originally reported to eBird by Gil Ewing; seen from ~10:50-11:10; eventually flew off to east. Quoting from Gil Ewing's email to the CVBirds list:  "Consensus is that it is a light-phased "Harlan’s” Red-tailed Hawk. As the Birding article by Brian Sullivan in 2010 said, Krider’s is not known to have occurred west of the Rockies.  Sonia [Santa Ana] first saw this bird at its current haunts on 2/19. Apparently this identifiably same individual hawk has already been seen and photographed on 2/21 by someone else and was already the subject of discussion by a large hawk identification group."

I know these sub-species  are tricky and maybe I have the wrong one but I think this one is worth flagging. The incoming distant bird almost gave me the feeling of a “Harlin’s” type as it got closer I knew it wasn’t ....I have never seen such a reddish color like this. The reddish color washed over the top of the breast, sides of head and flanks, the was also a reddish color in the shoulder bar, the heavy blotchy markings on breast band and the red showing well on the under tail feathers seem to indicate a western or northern sub-species.

Observation Details: Very well marked for the subspecies. Dark head blending into dark nape, spilling over the shoulders and dribbling onto the upper breast, the dark throat gives a very dark headed look. The belly band is dark with globular marks underpatterened with herringbone. The wings are extremely well marked with pattern throughout and a wide trailing band. The barred tarsus feathers are evident in some of the photos, and the tail shows ancillary barring with a prominent, wide terminal band. It wanted its photo taken as it passed over a a couple of times. Photo   ML446791911 is not cropped!

Observation Details: Possibly leucistic calurus.  Initially thought this might be a calurus x fuertesi, but unsure of the full range of variation in those subspecies.   While only having minimal streaking on the breast and flanks, the bird has a mostly dark throat (as opposed to the expected clean white throat of fuertesi), and some barring on the outermost rects rather than clean red tail with only the subterminal band that fuertesi should show.  From above, the white uppertail recalls the pattern shown by fuertesi.  This bird was paired up with another RTHA that looked to be on the pale end of what I normally see in light calurus.

Locality: McCarthy Park and Medfield State Hospital
Observation Details: I first saw the adult bird in the photos on a pole along the north side Hospital Road, very close to the railroad tracks.  It noticed me but seemed untroubled by my presence.  After some preening, the bird made as if it was ready to take off, and an instant later flew into brush about fifty feet from the pole, where it made a bit of a racket in the leaves.  The bird emerged with a chipmunk, carrying it (along with a fallen leaf or two) in a single claw, flew further into the woods, perched where it was still visible from the road, and began to eat.

Observation Details: I was fortunate to spend 15 minutes observing this sharp-looking juvenile as it pursued prey on the fringes of a marsh.  Per discussion on RTHOC FB Group the white head and darker collar, minimal patagials, weak belly-band, and washed-out base of tail suggest that this is a Krider-type or an intergrade with Borealis.  Many thanks to Mike Borlé for taking the time to assess this bird.

Discovered Robin nest above rear door of nature center. Hoping around upper deck and metal bars above second floor door. You could see the gears turning as it tried to figure out how to get to the nest. Several Robins and Blue jays were dive bombing, and became so intense at one point the Red-tail left. Two more fly-bys, and the Red-tail landed in a tall tree. I assumed the Red-tail had given up, but swooped down from  the tree, talons fully extended, and rammed strait into the nest like a wrecking ball. Scooped out 1 baby bird, and quickly flew off and landed on a nearby branch to dine. Many more birds joined the assault, until the Red-tail flew off into the deeper woods. Checked the nest and the other babies (2) were just fine, but I fear it won't be long before the Red-tail comes back. Incredible experience!

Today, I was minding my business when a red tailed hawk burst out from a tree, pursued by a grackle. It buzzed me so close, I felt the woosh of its wings on my face. Out of sorts, it sort of awkwardly crashlanded into a nearby bush. Still kinda shocked, I turned and yelled “what the hell, dude?” It craned its head around, and lit by a very cinematic sunbeam flashed this, the greatest troll face ever.

Had a few successful hunts right in front of me…

Light adult. Mostly gray tail mottled with fine black streaks, and definitely gray rather than the normal paleness of a regular RT tail. Remiges extremely varied in barring but all on a gray base, with some feathers having a lot of fine black marks, and others having wider barring. Heavy blotched belly band and heavy dark patagials.Heavily marked underwing coverts. Snowier white underside giving a much colder-looking apperance than the usual warm browns/oranges of most non-Harlan's.   Borealis aren't so gray/cold throughout, especially in the tail and remiges. Both borealis and abeticola have much more consistent barring in the underwings, while this bird varies almost by the feather.   I'm ashamed to say that I only noticed this upon reviewing photos a week later. Apologies to anyone who would have potentially tried for it that day. To my knowledge this is the first light Harlan's photographed in Wisconsin.

Collecting souvenir maybe?]

Locality: 1756 Norfolk County Road 19, Wilsonville, Ontario, CA (43.001, -80.199)
Media notes: 2077-15567; 1M. A touch on the small side, could be male of pair.
Observation Details: Pulled up to corner, spotted nest structure in tree ahead and noticed how nice this little patch of habitat was. Sure enough, as I turned the corner, scanning woodlot edges, I spotted a resident-type overlooking the meadow along the creek. This bird at first glance was small, with a flash of colour and buff below. It came in and then retreated to perch nearby, and in the time before I captured it a second larger, whiter bird had also appeared to perch close and watch. Presumably a resident pair.  Captured bird banded 2077-15567; 1M, after third cycle, but iris just pale enough that at first I thought I might expect it to be a younger bird.   Data collected as part of the Red-tailed Hawk Project. To learn more, please visit: https://redtailedhawkproject.org/

This bird at first glance was small, with a flash of colour and buff below. It came in and then retreated to perch nearby, and in the time before I captured it a second larger, whiter bird had also appeared to perch close and watch. Presumably a resident pair.  Captured bird banded 2077-15567; 1M, after third cycle, but iris just pale enough that at first I thought I might expect it to be a younger bird.   Data collected as part of the Red-tailed Hawk Project. To learn more, please visit: https://redtailedhawkproject.org/

Media notes: Captured and banded as part of the Red-tailed Hawk Project - www.redtailedhawkproject.org. Band #2187-18112 and color band Blue 9P. This bird, "Anj", also carries a transmitter so I will add the breeding location and migratory route to the website when it is available.

Captured and banded as part of the Red-tailed Hawk Project - www.redtailedhawkproject.org. Band #2187-18111 and color band Blue 6K. This individual, "Freya", also carries a transmitter. I will update the website with its breeding location and migratory routes when they are available. This bird is unique, and likely represents an intergrade from the contact zone in north west Canada. It has traits from multiple taxa, including a tail coloration and whitish and nearly unmarked upper tail coverts, reminiscent of what we see in kriderii, and high contrasting bird with irregular patterns in the banding of the flight feathers that indicate harlani influence, and an overall character to the body plumage pattern that suggests abieticola or the 'borealis' types that breed on the northern Great Plains. This bird is incredibly large in all measurements and mass, except with a moderate wing chord. This indicates it is almost certainly a female, but I will update once I sex it using PCR.

Observation Details: Watched for at least 15 minutes as a Red-tailed Hawk tried to get at a rabbit in a dogwood patch.  It repeatedly flew in close, hovered and dived into the dogwood but kept getting caught up and couldn't get to the rabbit.  Completely oblivious of me in its hunt, I was within 20' of it.  The rabbit did eventually make a sprint for it and the hawk pursued so I don't know the ending to this story! (Photo's)

Incredible rufous peanut butter undertail, pants and underwing coverts, and subtly rufous chest leaving just a shadow of a dark bellyband below.  Data collected as part of the Red-tailed Hawk Project. Appears to be at or near palest type per Wheeler's definition:  -- Paler overall than Eastern type -- Very white head -- Streaked white nape -- No dark malar mark -- Pale yellow eye -- Very faint patagial bars -- Strikingly white underparts -- Sparsely marked belly band -- Extensive white mottling on upperparts including white greater coverts with dark barring -- Almost completely white tail with narrow dark bands; hint of tan/rufous color on dorsal half

Initially seen perched in a tree & partially obscured by branches. I thought it was a Rough-legged at first but when it took flight I realized it was Redtailed that was much different then the usual birds from the area. Recently there have been discussions on the JERSEYBIRDS listserve about the abieticola subspecies & realized that might be what it was. Showed the pictures to some birders in Canada that seemed pretty certain of the ID. Spoke to another birder (Ron Shields) the day I saw it & he said it had been around for about a week. Could still be around but have not had a chance to get back there.

Locality: Quabbin Reservoir--Winsor Dam and Park Headquarters

Observation Details: 1 adult flyover and 1 bumbling immature who seems to be missing some primaries, see photos. I watched them a while and they spent a lot of time hopping and walking from place to place trying to hunt I think. I don't know enough about RTHA molts to say for sure if this is normal or an injury, but it didn't look good or like they could fly. Normally watching a hawk perched the way they were, they would be using their wings more to move about even going a short distance. This hawk was all hopping and walking. I will try to keep an eye on them when I am here and hope others will, too, in case they need a rehab. My photos were taken near the area at the end of the boardwalk with the rapids built by the beavers.

Media notes: "Ben". Captured and banded as part of the Red-tailed Hawk Project - www.redtailedhawkproject.org. Band #1857-02188 and color band Blue 6Y. This bird also now carries a GSM transmitter, and I will update its breeding location and migratory route on the website when these data are available. This bird is also an exciting recapture. It was first banded by Sylvain Bourdages in Grand Prairie, Alberta in May 2015. At the time, it was in juvenal plumage and just starting its second pre basic molt. Because of this, we know the individual is an eighth cycle. More details on this band recovery, including photos of the bird as a juvenile, can be found at https://redtailedhawkproject.org/2022/04/01/a-band-recovery-connecting-eastern-kansas-to-grand-prairie-alberta/

Second year male, banded and safely released on the day he turned 2. Serendipity at it's utmost. Ran into 2 biologists who were road trapping raptors, particularly RTHA's. I'm lucky enough to work as a wildlife biologist and have much experience handling raptors, so they let me join them for the day. Bal-chatris were the trap of the day. Happy New Year is right!. Elevation: 475 m. Date added to IBC: June 21, 2016.

Observation Details: Brian Sullivan's comments on this bird, received via e-mail:  As you've probably learned by now, light morph 1st-winter birds can be very challenging to ID to subspecies. This bird clearly has a pale face, but beyond that it's tough to say much about it. To ID kriderii and harlani you need good photos of the spread wings and tail, showing both the upper sides and the under sides. This bird could be a very pale-faced borealis, or a borealis x kriderii, or something cooler. Unfortunately we can't do much with just these two perched shots. I'm always happy to see any and all photos that you find interesting or challenging. You can never see too many Red-tailed Hawks!

We were very surprised to find this dark-rufous type adult with plumage details typical of the Northern/abieticola ssp but listed here, cautiously, as calurus/abieticola. There are only a handful of dark Red-tail records from Florida, and this one is one of the most southerly records for Northern/abieticola ever! Photos.

Dark head and eyes (with large white supercillium), a white throat separated from the breast by a dark line, broadly dark on sides of throat, head colour comes down over the breast in dense "dribbles", under colour of the breast is a dingy white, the belly band is wider outside and narrow in the centre, an under pattern of herringbone can be seen on lower belly.

Media notes: A Juvenile Red-Tailed Hawk photographed at the Crow's Nest Natural Area Preserve in Stafford, Virginia.
Observation Details: This is a Juvenile Red Tailed Hawk photographed in the forest of the Crow's Nest Natural Area Preserve in Stafford, Virginia.  I was walking on a trail through deep forest, when I noticed a large Hawk sitting atop a broken tree stump.  The bird sat for at least 15 minutes, and allowed me to photograph her, showing no fear or agitation with my presence.  This forest is very dark, with low light conditions for photography, yet a gentle ray of sun came between the trees and lit this bird beautifully, allowing me to have enough natural light to photograph her.  This was a very special moment for me.
All appeared to be of normal plumage.

Presumed "Northern" RTHA (abieticola); stunning adult; prominent dark belly band; dark head and throat, the latter almost completely so, with markings extending into belly band; bold patagial marks; dark upperparts; deep red uppertail with partial barring; photos.   Dorsal notes were taken strictly off photos as I only really saw the underside well before I started shooting and only saw the upperside briefly through camera.  Today's bird was a brief encounter as it made a quick but stunning and close pass in great light then circled once before being carried east by strong winds. I've resisted seperating these on eBird till now but as long as reports are well described (or better yet photographed) then ebirding these should only help our understanding.

One of my cooler raptor experiences. At least two, and possibly three immature birds were incredibly active towards the point - fighting and scraping with each other, and flying incredibly low right overhead multiple times. Once, one of them flew less than 10 feet over my head - they seemed to show absolutely no fear of humans.  One immature bird flew out over the water, towards UMass, which seemed pretty odd.  The second immature bird, which stayed and hunted around the point, hand a metal band, but no plastic band. Band # 2187-09850

Captured and banded as part of the Red-tailed Hawk Project - www.redtailedhawkproject.org. Band #2187-11170 and color band Blue 8H. I put this bird in as an abieticola but it is almost certainly form the contact zone with birds we consider to belong to the northern extent of calurus. In other words, it's fairly typical for the 'abieticola' we find in Kansas during winter, but it does differ from birds that winter in areas of New York, for instance. Traits in this bird that indicate this are a slightly more extensive patagium, rufous markings in the bellyband, rich buffy base color, golden head, and hints of barring in the undertail. Likely a male by morphometrics. I'll update after I sex it using PCR.

Media notes: 2207 02009. Female based on measurements and very pronounced brood patch.
Observation Details: An absolutely gorgeous, very spicy female. Was on the trap before the dust behind me cleared. Banded 2207-02009. Very pronounced brood patch, just beginning to feather over with six or seven pin feathers emerging but no other signs of body moult yet. Very vocal upon release, and other, more distant cries seemed likely enough to be fledglings.  Data collected as part of the Red-tailed Hawk Project. To learn more, please visit: https://redtailedhawkproject.org/  *Update: Found injured at 59437 County Road 13, Mountain Lake, Cottonwood County, Minnesota on 1 October 2021. Captured alive and brought to rehabilitation center, where it was euthanized due to a grave prognosis for recovery.

Media notes: Light phase "Harlan's" Red-tailed Hawk, El Dorado Hills, El Dorado County, California
Observation Details: Continuing light phase originally reported to eBird by Gil Ewing; seen from ~10:50-11:10; eventually flew off to east. Quoting from Gil Ewing's email to the CVBirds list:  "Consensus is that it is a light-phased "Harlan’s” Red-tailed Hawk. As the Birding article by Brian Sullivan in 2010 said, Krider’s is not known to have occurred west of the Rockies.  Sonia [Santa Ana] first saw this bird at its current haunts on 2/19. Apparently this identifiably same individual hawk has already been seen and photographed on 2/21 by someone else and was already the subject of discussion by a large hawk identification group."

I first spotted this hawk perched on a branch on the golf course side of the parkway, studying the ground below it. It stayed there for quite a while and didn't pay me any mind when I crossed the street and hunkered down to photograph it. Eventually it came to ground, looking as though it had captured something, repeatedly looking at its feet buried in long dried grasses. When it flew up to a tangle of vines nearby, it has nothing. It perched on the pile for a little while, right in front of me, before flying up to sit on a different branch. A Blue Jay acted only slightly offended by its presence, but the hawk behaved as if there was no Blue Jay at all. Eventually it flew up the road to land in a tree too distant to photograph it in. This entire timeframe lasted nearly 20 minutes.

Media notes: "Ben". Captured and banded as part of the Red-tailed Hawk Project - www.redtailedhawkproject.org. Band #1857-02188 and color band Blue 6Y. This bird also now carries a GSM transmitter, and I will update its breeding location and migratory route on the website when these data are available. This bird is also an exciting recapture. It was first banded by Sylvain Bourdages in Grand Prairie, Alberta in May 2015. At the time, it was in juvenal plumage and just starting its second pre basic molt. Because of this, we know the individual is an eighth cycle. More details on this band recovery, including photos of the bird as a juvenile, can be found at https://redtailedhawkproject.org/2022/04/01/a-band-recovery-connecting-eastern-kansas-to-grand-prairie-alberta/

Initially submitted the species as a regular buteo jamaicenses but after consulting experts that analyzed  pictures taken we decided to change to this subspecies.According to RYAN PHILLIPS the brick red tail,dark throat,heavy belly band,dark outer primary tips all say calurus subspecies.ALSO consulting with Brian Sullivan he said calurus no traits of any other subspecies.We strongly believe its a migrant subspecies that should be considered as such and not just a normal red tail hawk.MEDIA to be included both from ISAIAS MORATAYA and RONI MARTINEZ.

1 adult flyover and 1 bumbling immature who seems to be missing some primaries, see photos. I watched them a while and they spent a lot of time hopping and walking from place to place trying to hunt I think. I don't know enough about RTHA molts to say for sure if this is normal or an injury, but it didn't look good or like they could fly. Normally watching a hawk perched the way they were, they would be using their wings more to move about even going a short distance. This hawk was all hopping and walking. I will try to keep an eye on them when I am here and hope others will, too, in case they need a rehab. My photos were taken near the area at the end of the boardwalk with the rapids built by the beavers.

Observation Details: Brian Sullivan's comments on this bird, received via e-mail:  As you've probably learned by now, light morph 1st-winter birds can be very challenging to ID to subspecies. This bird clearly has a pale face, but beyond that it's tough to say much about it. To ID kriderii and harlani you need good photos of the spread wings and tail, showing both the upper sides and the under sides. This bird could be a very pale-faced borealis, or a borealis x kriderii, or something cooler. Unfortunately we can't do much with just these two perched shots. I'm always happy to see any and all photos that you find interesting or challenging. You can never see too many Red-tailed Hawks!

1 adult flyover and 1 bumbling immature who seems to be missing some primaries, see photos. I watched them a while and they spent a lot of time hopping and walking from place to place trying to hunt I think. I don't know enough about RTHA molts to say for sure if this is normal or an injury, but it didn't look good or like they could fly. Normally watching a hawk perched the way they were, they would be using their wings more to move about even going a short distance. This hawk was all hopping and walking. I will try to keep an eye on them when I am here and hope others will, too, in case they need a rehab. My photos were taken near the area at the end of the boardwalk with the rapids built by the beavers.

Locality: Carretera al Nor-oeste de Rancho Ebenezer

Observation Details: Perched on a fence post along highway 170 just west of the turnoff to Lyons Lake. The bird completely lacked the bellyband of a typical RTHA (although photos show very faint streaking on flanks). The patagial bars were rusty and faint. The tail was mostly white, but the distal third was reddish. The upperparts showed extensive white mottling, especially on the scapulars. The lesser upperwing coverts were distinctly rufous. The head was also mottled with white and the bird had a broad white supercillium.

Locality: Hahamongna Watershed Park (formerly Oak Grove Park)

Observation Details: Each of two red-tails were observed to be repeatedly carrying sticks into a white pine stand. We saw at least three trips. When we were close to the trees each circled above us while carrying a stick. We quickly exited the area to let them continue. One of the birds had a silver metal band on its R leg and its markings resembled those of the male of the pair that successfully nested last season. The unbanded bird had very sparse belly streaking which was consistent with what was seen on the female from last year's pair. This is at least the 4th year that the banded hawk has been seen and photographed in the arboretum.

Two juveniles and two adults. One juvenile was in on the ground in a fallow field and had problems taking off from the ground. It called constantly and pitifully to its parents. After glaring at me for a few minutes, it hopped along the ground for about ten yards before it could get airborne and and immediately tripped over the air and crashed head first. The youngster shook itself and spread its wings and looked at them hard, then jumped into the air and took flight, heading to a dead tree. That landing took two attempts. The second bird, which seemed a little older, was perched on a power pole and also called constantly. I saw both adults in the air and hunting from poles in the fields. One parent brought a part of a mammal of some kind to the poled perched youngster. The young bird grabbed the food with one foot and the parent flew off.

Media notes: Mottled tail pattern helps ID this individual as a Harlan's, not Krider's. The plumage is leucistic, which isn't that unusual in Harlan's.  Eye color is gold, but molting plumage indicates this bird is in its second calendar year and second plumage cycle.
Observation Details: "The mottled tail pattern here helps ID this individual as a Harlan's, not Krider's. The plumage is leucistic, which isn't that unusual in Harlan's, though this bird is a nice copy of what we'd look for in general for Krider's." -  Thanks to  Brian Sullivan for correction from what was previously reported as Krider's.  I previously had aged this as a Juvenile based upon eye color, however thanks to Tony Leukering for this clarification - "The bird is in wing and tail molt, and also has wide and quite black tips to the new remiges.  Thus, this bird is in its second calendar year and second plumage cycle; it is not an HY."  Relatively small talon size indicates that this is a male.

Initially ID'd at the time as calurus, as I was unfamiliar with abieticola. The very heavy belly band, limited rufous wash to chest, and relatively indistinct banding in wings make me now think abieticola is the better option. The one mark that is pro calurus is the fairly heavy barring on thighs and belly, which most but evidently not all abieticola lack.

Media notes: Chasing after her prey, a plains garter snake
Observation Details: I've seen this red-tailed hawk at the lake many times, but today as I was crossing the prairie area to the southwest, she swooped down into the field. It looked as if she was picking at something on the ground, and it turned out to be a garter snake! She pecked at it a few times, and followed the snake for about 5 yards stomping on it with her talons as it tried to make an escape, before finally getting a hold of it in her beak. Super cool to see this common predator in action!

It stood there, I got off a few pictures, and then as I raised my binoculars again, it took off, flying over me with what sounded like heh heh, and swept over to also fly over the people standing on the bridge. Decided nothing was going to top that and went home.

Two juveniles and two adults. One juvenile was in on the ground in a fallow field and had problems taking off from the ground. It called constantly and pitifully to its parents. After glaring at me for a few minutes, it hopped along the ground for about ten yards before it could get airborne and and immediately tripped over the air and crashed head first. The youngster shook itself and spread its wings and looked at them hard, then jumped into the air and took flight, heading to a dead tree. That landing took two attempts. The second bird, which seemed a little older, was perched on a power pole and also called constantly. I saw both adults in the air and hunting from poles in the fields. One parent brought a part of a mammal of some kind to the poled perched youngster. The young bird grabbed the food with one foot and the parent flew off.

Media notes: Note pattern on secondary tips, with pale blotch on inner web.
Observation Details: Finally had a chance to go see this juvenile bird, which had been reported since late January. Close inspection of details of the secondaries, primaries, and tail, reveal enough characters to support the ID has Harlan's, though an intergrade with Western cannot be ruled out entirely. Note especially the pattern of the secondary tips, which are dark with white blotches on the inner webs. The banding in the primaries is somewhat wavy, especially on the upperside, and there is a suggestion of mottling at the bases of the outer 6 primaries. The banding in the flight feathers and tail is thicker than what would be expected on Western, and better for Harlan's. Tail pattern in unusual in having thick bands that fade out near the base; uppertail coverts all-dark--also unusual. Solid dark juveniles like this are rare in Western, and more common in Harlan's, though Harlan's usually has a blacker ground color--not always. This bird is at the dark extreme for a juvenile Red-tailed Hawk of any subspecies, lacking any obvious pattern. It really requires close study to see the details needed to confirm the ID as Harlan's, and luckily this bird is obliging when it is in view. This bird's behavior is unusual in two ways: it is very tame, unlike most Harlan's; and it is quite sneaky, staying low, perch-hunting from edge and some exposed perches, but not getting up to soar much.

Media notes: I stood outside my car for a full hour (I believe) watching this amazing Hawk just preening itself and watching the Ravens. It was soooo windy it was hard to get many salvageable shots of almost any birds, but this Hawk is very accommodating. When it took off eventually it flew east north east towards Rue Des Trappistes area where it also hangs out.
Observation Details: At its usual location in a tree near the building at 49.759725, -97.179473. I observed it for just over an hour. It spent most of the time cleaning itself and interestingly enough stretching its legs out repeatedly and pulling one up under its feathers. I assume that was to keep them warm one at a time and stretch out any cramps or stiffness (if birds get that).

Horribly injured. Spotted sitting initially on a large log. Nearby Ravens kept flying at it, threatening it. It eventually took off and flew unsteadily about 300m away into a stand of trees where it was more protected in the branches. Absolutely heart breaking. Notice the caked on ice over the eyes, the blood around the bill, the unkept feathers on the head, blood near the belly/tail area, and missing flight feathers.

1 adult flyover and 1 bumbling immature who seems to be missing some primaries, see photos. I watched them a while and they spent a lot of time hopping and walking from place to place trying to hunt I think. I don't know enough about RTHA molts to say for sure if this is normal or an injury, but it didn't look good or like they could fly. Normally watching a hawk perched the way they were, they would be using their wings more to move about even going a short distance. This hawk was all hopping and walking. I will try to keep an eye on them when I am here and hope others will, too, in case they need a rehab. My photos were taken near the area at the end of the boardwalk with the rapids built by the beavers.

Locality: Samish Flats "T"--Bayview Edison & Samish Island Rd

Observation Details: The hawk was initially perched at the very top of spruce tree, by the administrative buildings. From this position it could see rodents both inside the airport fence, as well as rodents outside the airport fence on the soccer fields. After looking at the photo more carefully, I could see that the hawk had grabbed the top branch of the spruce tree in such a way that the weight of the hawk “loaded” the branch like a catapult. When the hawk eventually flew, it got the launching benefit of the weight loaded “spring” of the branch. It’s next perch was 300 feet away on a tall weather measurement utility pole, where it perched closer to the airport runway, and continued to hunt for rodents.

One of my cooler raptor experiences. At least two, and possibly three immature birds were incredibly active towards the point - fighting and scraping with each other, and flying incredibly low right overhead multiple times. Once, one of them flew less than 10 feet over my head - they seemed to show absolutely no fear of humans.  One immature bird flew out over the water, towards UMass, which seemed pretty odd.  The second immature bird, which stayed and hunted around the point, hand a metal band, but no plastic band. Band # 2187-09850

Captured and banded as part of the Red-tailed Hawk Project - www.redtailedhawkproject.org. Band #1947-07687 and color band Blue 4Y. Maybe best characterized as an intergrade because of the barred uppertail coverts, barring in flanks, and lack of spectacled look from white supercilium and under eye. Tail pattern is interesting in being heavily banded and washed out, but with some regularity to the banding that is reminiscent of harlani.

Horribly injured. Spotted sitting initially on a large log. Nearby Ravens kept flying at it, threatening it. It eventually took off and flew unsteadily about 300m away into a stand of trees where it was more protected in the branches. Absolutely heart breaking. Notice the caked on ice over the eyes, the blood around the bill, the unkept feathers on the head, blood near the belly/tail area, and missing flight feathers.

Perched on a post, flew off while we were still a long way back but swept up to land not too far off on a tall dead tree so I swung off and threw for it anyway. Captured and banded 2077-15528. Unexpectedly gorgeous in the hand after such a fleeting glimpse in the field. Overall good for abieticola, but tail with dense mottling at the base suggests some harlani lineage. An older cycle female with a full brood patch, just beginning to moult. Second bird flew off from nearby concealed perch further back, lighter overall with a plain red tail.  Data collected as part of the Red-tailed Hawk Project. To learn more, please visit: https://redtailedhawkproject.org/

Media notes: 2207 02009. Female based on measurements and very pronounced brood patch.
Observation Details: An absolutely gorgeous, very spicy female. Was on the trap before the dust behind me cleared. Banded 2207-02009. Very pronounced brood patch, just beginning to feather over with six or seven pin feathers emerging but no other signs of body moult yet. Very vocal upon release, and other, more distant cries seemed likely enough to be fledglings.  Data collected as part of the Red-tailed Hawk Project. To learn more, please visit: https://redtailedhawkproject.org/  *Update: Found injured at 59437 County Road 13, Mountain Lake, Cottonwood County, Minnesota on 1 October 2021. Captured alive and brought to rehabilitation center, where it was euthanized due to a grave prognosis for recovery.

Observation Details: Potentially the most stunning encounter I've had in my life. Absolutely gorgeous and fearless Red-Tailed Hawk. I saw it sitting in the trees and pulled over to try and take a few pictures when it flew down to eye level and perched in a leafless shrub. There it sat looking around seemingly perch hunting. I was very close to it already so I walked a bit closer. The hawk watched me intently and with curiosity as I approached but remained very calm the whole time. Eventually, I got within FIVE FEET of the hawk. If I had leaned forward I would have been able to pet its head. It was surreal seeing a completely wild hawk so close. As I got within that limit, the hawk started flinching so I stopped approaching and backed up a tiny bit so I didn't stress him. Then after staring at me for a while he went back to his business, looking around and also preening. I sat there for nearly a half hour with a wild Red-Tailed Hawk just feet ahead of me at nearly eye level. It was absolutely gorgeous. Finally, after nearly a half hour of sitting beside him, the hawk leaped off the branch and flew to a lamp post. I left him after that. Wow that was an insane encounter!!!  He (or she) was a young bird currently molting into adult plumage. Part of its fearlessness may have been due to its young age.

Locality: 365-101 Concession Road 2, Port Rowan, Ontario, CA (42.602, -80.567)
Media notes: Juvenal tail on bird moulting into second cycle basic plumage.
Observation Details: Adult perched on wire, balancing a wobbly wobble into the wind, took flight as we approached but immediately banked to perch again so set the trap a short way down. It flew immediately to sit above with interest, dropping down onto the very center. At this moment a second bird out of the sky was descending slowly yet eagerly, feet slightly extended. It didn't land but banked and continued to watch from a controlled, low arc over the field. The bird on the trap wasn't properly caught as we approached and flew off, but it came back around in a tight circle so we rolled past. Just moments later this second bird swooped in and was caught.   Banded 2207 02005. Undergoing a second prebasic moult! P1^2 and P2^1, perfectly symmetric. No signs of moult among tertials on either wing. Three breast feathers newly replaced basic, as well as a dozen or so scapulars. Fluffy gaps throughout back and crown suggested active body moult, but could only locate one pin on the capital tract amidst all of the fluff.

Observation Details: Pulled up to corner, spotted nest structure in tree ahead and noticed how nice this little patch of habitat was. Sure enough, as I turned the corner, scanning woodlot edges, I spotted a resident-type overlooking the meadow along the creek. This bird at first glance was small, with a flash of colour and buff below. It came in and then retreated to perch nearby, and in the time before I captured it a second larger, whiter bird had also appeared to perch close and watch. Presumably a resident pair.  Captured bird banded 2077-15567; 1M, after third cycle, but iris just pale enough that at first I thought I might expect it to be a younger bird.   Data collected as part of the Red-tailed Hawk Project. To learn more, please visit: https://redtailedhawkproject.org/

Las Abras, Provincia de Cartago, CR (9.996, -83.723)
Las Abras, Provincia de Cartago, CR (9.996, -83.723)

Observation Details: Some very interesting behavior going on here. For pretty much my whole walk, I was aware of at least one of these hawks circling around the hill (though I initially came upon one perched and being harassed by robins and cardinals). At one point, one tried to land in a tree just ahead of me, apparently misjudged its branch, started to fall, then swooped to a different tree across the street. I saw them soaring together at one point. And then ... one of them came flying low into a small clearing where I was sitting, found itself a nice camouflaged perch, and seemed to be hiding from the other one, which circled around for awhile before vanishing. Curious! The one that came and perched near me was an immature bird; didn't get a good enough look at the other who I only saw high up.

Locality: McDonald Road, up the Mill Road

Observation Details: Nest in Boggs deodar; this nest has been used at least since the 1990s.  When I first arrived, only 2 adults were visible.  Later, I noticed one juvenile perched just N of the nest.  As I was leaving, I checked again, and I saw one, then two heads poke out of the foliage next to the earlier viewed juvenile--so 3 youngsters--way to go, Mom & Dad!

Pretty cool experience at the bird feeder station. This hawk landed feet from me while I was observing blackbirds and attempted to snag a chipmunk. The chipmunk hid under this wheelbarrow and the hawk tried several ways of capturing the chipmunk. Beak first, talon first, hopping from side to side. This went on for a good 10 minutes at least and was still going on when I left. I'm unsure whether the hawk was ever successful.

Pretty cool experience at the bird feeder station. This hawk landed feet from me while I was observing blackbirds and attempted to snag a chipmunk. The chipmunk hid under this wheelbarrow and the hawk tried several ways of capturing the chipmunk. Beak first, talon first, hopping from side to side. This went on for a good 10 minutes at least and was still going on when I left. I'm unsure whether the hawk was ever successful.

Media notes: Adult captured and banded 2187-18137; 7T. This bird also now wears a GPS/GSM transmitter, 0086, 'Grizzly'. Locality: IRWD San Joaquin Marsh & Wildlife Sanctuary, Irvine

Observation Details: This bird caught my attention as being almost abieticola-like with the dark chin, rufous streaks above belly band, thick "splotchy" belly band, and very dark patagials. I've been told subspecies identification is particularly tough in downstate NY when a bird falls somewhere in the middle of the borealis-abieticola spectrum like this one, so I'm omitting subspecies here.

Locality: Ash Canyon Bird Sanctuary (closed Thursday morning; formerly Ash Canyon B&B)
West Wilshire Boulevard Northeast, El Reno, Oklahoma, US (35.551, -97.853)
Media notes: 1967-08689. Data collected as part of the Red-tailed Hawk Project. To learn more, please visit: https://redtailedhawkproject.org/
Observation Details: Approaching junction from the west spotted a pale-bellied, brown-headed bird perched ahead to the north. As I stopped to put binoculars on it, it flew, heading directly west. I angled the car to follow as it swooped up to land, right on top of a second bird which I had missed perched on a snag now behind me. The two copulated for five or six seconds, and I watched just long enough to see the male land to the left of the female before spinning around. As I turned, I watched the male lift off and fly south out of sight. The female remained in her original place, and responded in less five seconds.  Banded 1967-08689. Clear beginnings of a brood patch, with sparse down feathers and very heavy fluid beneath the skin on the lowermost belly above the cloaca. Firm mass in middle abdomen, possibly gravid?  After release, she circled back to land in trees behind her original perch. Male returned and the pair vocalized before copulating again. This time, both birds flew afterward, calling, and disappeared further north into woods. From road along east side of woods a large nest structure was visible, and perched next to it (~10m away) was a bird which after some patience watching in the scope, shuffled to clearly display a band on her right leg.   Data collected as part of the Red-tailed Hawk Project. To learn more, please visit: https://redtailedhawkproject.org/

Locality: West Wilshire Boulevard Northeast, El Reno, Oklahoma, US (35.551, -97.853)
Media notes: 1967-08689. Data collected as part of the Red-tailed Hawk Project. To learn more, please visit: https://redtailedhawkproject.org/
Observation Details: Approaching junction from the west spotted a pale-bellied, brown-headed bird perched ahead to the north. As I stopped to put binoculars on it, it flew, heading directly west. I angled the car to follow as it swooped up to land, right on top of a second bird which I had missed perched on a snag now behind me. The two copulated for five or six seconds, and I watched just long enough to see the male land to the left of the female before spinning around. As I turned, I watched the male lift off and fly south out of sight. The female remained in her original place, and responded in less five seconds.  Banded 1967-08689. Clear beginnings of a brood patch, with sparse down feathers and very heavy fluid beneath the skin on the lowermost belly above the cloaca. Firm mass in middle abdomen, possibly gravid?  After release, she circled back to land in trees behind her original perch. Male returned and the pair vocalized before copulating again. This time, both birds flew afterward, calling, and disappeared further north into woods. From road along east side of woods a large nest structure was visible, and perched next to it (~10m away) was a bird which after some patience watching in the scope, shuffled to clearly display a band on her right leg.   Data collected as part of the Red-tailed Hawk Project. To learn more, please visit: https://redtailedhawkproject.org/

Media notes: After third cycle banded 2207-02035; 4N. Data collected as part of the Red-tailed Hawk Project. To learn more, please visit: https://redtailedhawkproject.org/
Observation Details: Initial response from one bird with apparently smaller proportions and slightly heavier bellyband. Second bird flew over to land on opposite side of woodlot to the north then captured and banded 2207-02035; 4N. At least fourth cycle, with a minimum of three blocks of replaced primaries. Asymmetric. Likely a female, relatively large. Peculiar 'blurry' left pupil suggesting a possible cataract or loss of vision, and the bird seemed less responsive to movement on this side.   Data collected as part of the Red-tailed Hawk Project. To learn more, please visit: https://redtailedhawkproject.org/

Very cold toned individual. Black spotted belly band, thick, wavy tail banding, blackish marks on neck and upper breast, dark streaking on an otherwise white crown, extensive spangling on the topside with no warm tones. The rufous tinged tail color is likely due to mixing with another subspecies, probably making this bird a Harlan’s intergrade. Very striking bird!

Locality: McCarthy Park and Medfield State Hospital
Observation Details: I first saw the adult bird in the photos on a pole along the north side Hospital Road, very close to the railroad tracks.  It noticed me but seemed untroubled by my presence.  After some preening, the bird made as if it was ready to take off, and an instant later flew into brush about fifty feet from the pole, where it made a bit of a racket in the leaves.  The bird emerged with a chipmunk, carrying it (along with a fallen leaf or two) in a single claw, flew further into the woods, perched where it was still visible from the road, and began to eat.
Millie ❤️
